narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: General knowledge of philosophy and writing
Knowledge of philosophical writings and thinkers as well as the skill to write philosophically and understand different thinkings
Introductory survey knowledge of philosophy.
Epistemology, metaphysics, logical reasoning, ethics, meaning of life
I learned about some of the great philosophers, and I learned how to think critically about basic questions.

Basic knowledge of specific philosophers 
Understanding with discussions of life and knowledge
Not particular skills but a way of thinking and exploration
A great survey of the discipline of philosophy

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I liked the course, taught me a lot
I think it was a very strong class. I just think that the writing was graded quite harshly considering we only talked about philosophy, not how to write.

I think a little bit more of an introduction on philosophical writing before our first assignment could have been nice, but overall it was structured well. I think we covered a good breadth of philosophers, but wish we could have covered more things related to practical applications (ie., some of what we covered at the end with the quartet) as opposed to purely theoretical ideas.
Good selection of materials for readings, great lectures, great discussions.
Strengths: very expansive coverage of philosophy, engaging seminars

I thought the course was very well organized; the readings made sense together and complemented (or contradicted) one another in interesting ways. Discussion was friendly but rigorous, and both the professor and TA always made themselves available to students.

The course content is sometimes concentrated on some non-typical course materials
And the grader is too tough
But the lecturer is nice and easygoing
Good good dood.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, it was cool
Yes. Great intro class with interesting discussion and readings

Yes, however, be prepared that it is very theoretical. I enjoyed the way Prof Franks clearly explained big takeaways from each of our readings every week, which is great to facilitate learning. However, if you are looking for philosophy with a more practical application, take a course that is more specific to a certain discipline of philosophy.
Yes, anyone who wants to start pondering the big questions should take this course.
Yes, if you are interested in philosophy and ready to devote your time to readings and analysis

I would recommend this course to pretty much anyone. The readings are fascinating. Even more importantly, the class taught me how to think about those readings, how to consider their limitations and their assumptions. I learned to extend this way of thinking to my own arguments and my own writing.

It's reading-intensive and challenging. But equally interesting.
Perhaps, but it seemed quite hard to obtain positive motivation as a 1 level intro course.
yes.
Yes. Good survey course with a great teacher.
